definition.value: Discrimination against persons' based on their gender role, identity, and/or expression.
Discrimination based on aspects of a person's sex- or gender-related characteristics, or the perception of such characteristics.

The belief in the superiority of one race over another. It may also include prejudice, discrimination, or antagonism directed against other people because they are of a different race or ethnicity, or the belief that members of different races or ethnicities should be treated differently.
Stereotyping and discrimination against individuals or groups on the basis of their age.
Discrimination relating to social class.
Discrimination or prejudice that is based on social class.
A form of prejudice or discrimination usually from members of the same race in which people are treated differently based on the social implications from cultural meanings attached to skin color.
Discrimination against persons based on their disability status.
Discrimination and social prejudice against people with disabilities or who are perceived to have disabilities.
Systematic discrimination against young persons.
The discrimination against older people in favor of younger persons.
The social practice of visually underrepresenting older people or misrepresenting them in a prejudiced way.
The prejudices faced by older adults in the digital world.

A form of racism expressed in the practice of social and political institutions. It is reflected in disparities regarding wealth, income, criminal justice, employment, housing, health care, political power and education, among other factors.

Pseudoscientific belief that empirical evidence exists to support or justify racism (racial discrimination), racial inferiority, or racial superiority. Historically, scientific racism received credence throughout the scientific community, but it is no longer considered scientific.
Note that modern scientific racist ideas and proponents have attempted to rebrand their ideas as "race realism" and "human biodiversity".
Discrimination related to a person or persons' caste.
Discrimination based on a person's caste.
Discrimination based on one's sexual orientation.
The belief that one set of sexual behaviors is intrinsically superior to another set of sexual behaviors, or prejudice and discrimination based on that belief.
The hatred of, contempt for, or prejudice against men or boys in general.
The hatred of, contempt for, or prejudice against women or girls.
Dislike or hatred of oneself, or being angry at or even prejudiced against oneself.
The general hatred, dislike, distrust or contempt of the human species or human nature.
An intense dislike or disgust of oneself.

A lack of knowledge and information. The word "ignorant" is an adjective that describes a person in the state of being unaware, and can describe individuals who deliberately ignore or disregard important information or facts, or individuals who are unaware of important information or facts. Ignorance can appear in three different types: factual ignorance (absence of knowledge of some fact), objectual ignorance (unacquaintance with some object), and technical ignorance (absence of knowledge of how to do something).
The condition of being uninformed or uneducated. Lack of knowledge or information.

A psychological construct, a mental and emotional entity that inheres in, or characterizes a person. They are complex and are an acquired state through experiences. It is an individual's predisposed state of mind regarding a value[disambiguation needed] and it is precipitated through a responsive expression towards a person, place, thing, or event (the attitude object) which in turn influences the individual's thought and action.

Bias is disproportionate weight in favor of or against an idea or thing, usually in a way that is closed-minded, prejudicial, or unfair. Biases can be innate or learned. People may develop biases for or against an individual, a group, or a belief.
A belief is a proposition that is believed to be true.
The attitude that something is the case or true.

A systematic pattern of deviation from norm or rationality in judgment. Individuals create their own "subjective social reality" from their perception of the input. An individual's construction of social reality, not the objective input, may dictate their behaviour in the social world. Thus, cognitive biases may sometimes lead to perceptual distortion, inaccurate judgment, illogical interpretation, or what is broadly called irrationality.
Biases which occur when a person is influenced by extraneous information.
The phenomenon of interpreting and judging phenomena by standards inherent to one's own culture.
Surgical procedures performed on parts of the thyroid cartilage.
Bias against LGBTQIA+ people based on their identities, namely sexual orientation identity and gender identity.
Bias against one based on their race.
Discrimination against persons based on their physical appearance or physicality.
Prejudice or discrimination on the grounds of a person's appearance.
Exaggeration or preference of a person's features or appearance in relationship to political office.
Bias against one based on their physical appearance.
Bias against one based on their ethnicity.
Bias against one based on their gender.
Bias against gay people, in particular gay men.
Bias against transgender people.
Discrimination against a person or group on the basis of their sexual orientation or sexual behavior.
Biases based on one's caste.

An affective feeling towards a person based on that person's perceived group membership. The word is often used to refer to a preconceived, usually unfavorable, evaluation of another person based on that person's political affiliation, sex, gender, beliefs, values, social class, age, disability, religion, sexuality, race/ethnicity, language, nationality, beauty, occupation, education, criminality, sport team affiliation or other personal characteristics.
Discrimination based on one's mental health status or related conditions.

A system of attitudes, bias, and discrimination in favor of opposite-sex sexuality and relationships. It can include the presumption that other people are heterosexual or that opposite-sex attractions and relationships are the only norm and therefore superior.
Discrimination against non-cisgender (transgender) persons.
Discrimination against persons not adhering to binary gender norms, typically nonbinary persons.
Discrimination against LGBTQ persons.
